# Component Development Workflow

This rule defines the structured workflow for building features from UI design through API integration. Follow these steps to ensure consistent, maintainable, and testable components.

## Development Process Overview

The component development process follows this order:

1. **API Route with Mock Data** - Create Next.js API route that returns mock data
2. **UI Component** - Build the component that fetches from your API endpoint
3. **Implement Real Data** - Replace mock data with real database queries (component unchanged)
4. **Testing** - Use MSW to test component behavior

**Key Principles:** 
- Always create Next.js API routes (not MSW) for your own APIs
- MSW is only for external APIs you don't control or for testing
- No environment variables needed - just update the API route code
- Component code never changes when switching from mock to real data

## Phase 1: Create API Route with Mock Data

Start by creating a Next.js API route that returns mock data. This is the standard approach for all your internal APIs.

### Step 1.1: Create Next.js API Route

```typescript
// Good: app/api/users/[id]/route.ts - Start with mock data
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";

export async function GET(
  request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: { id: string } }
) {
  // Mock data for initial development
  const mockUser = {
    id: params.id,
    name: "John Doe",
    email: "john@example.com",
    avatar: "/avatars/john.jpg",
    role: "Admin",
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };

  // Optional: Add realistic delay to simulate network
  // await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 500));

  return NextResponse.json(mockUser);
}
```

**When to Use MSW Instead:**
- ❌ Never for your own APIs - always create API routes
- ✅ Only for external APIs you don't control (e.g., `api.stripe.com`, `api.github.com`)
- ✅ Automatically in tests (already configured in `@repo/vitest`)

### Step 1.2: Include Edge Cases in Mock Data

Create handlers for different scenarios:

```typescript
// Good: Multiple scenarios in API route
export async function GET(
  request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: { id: string } }
) {
  // Simulate error for testing
  if (params.id === "error") {
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: "User not found" },
      { status: 404 }
    );
  }

  // Simulate slow response for testing
  if (params.id === "slow") {
    await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 3000));
  }

  // Return mock data
  const mockUser = {
    id: params.id,
    name: params.id === "long" 
      ? "Very Long Name That Might Break The Layout Design" 
      : "John Doe",
    email: "john@example.com",
    avatar: "/avatars/john.jpg",
    role: "Admin",
  };

  return NextResponse.json(mockUser);
}
```

## Phase 2: Build UI Component

Now build the UI component that fetches from your API endpoint. The component remains unchanged whether using mock or real data.

### Step 2.1: Create Component with API Integration

```typescript
// Good: Component fetches from API endpoint from the start
interface UserProfileProps {
  userId: string;
}

export function UserProfile({ userId }: UserProfileProps) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState<Error | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    async function fetchUser() {
      try {
        setLoading(true);
        const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`);
        
        if (!response.ok) {
          throw new Error("Failed to fetch user");
        }
        
        const data = await response.json();
        setUser(data);
      } catch (err) {
        setError(err as Error);
      } finally {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    }

    fetchUser();
  }, [userId]);

  // Handle all states...
  if (loading) return <Skeleton />;
  if (error) return <ErrorMessage error={error} />;
  if (!user) return null;

  return (
    <Card>
      <CardHeader>
        <CardTitle>{user.name}</CardTitle>
        <CardDescription>{user.email}</CardDescription>
      </CardHeader>
      <CardContent>
        <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
          <Avatar>
            <AvatarImage src={user.avatar} />
            <AvatarFallback>{user.name[0]}</AvatarFallback>
          </Avatar>
          <div>
            <p className="text-sm font-medium">{user.role}</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </CardContent>
    </Card>
  );
}
```

### Step 2.2: Design All UI States

Build UI for all possible states using the API:

```typescript
// Good: All states handled, data comes from API
export function UserList() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState<User[]>([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState<Error | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch("/api/users")
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(setUsers)
      .catch(setError)
      .finally(() => setLoading(false));
  }, []);

  if (loading) {
    return <TableSkeleton />;
  }

  if (error) {
    return (
      <Alert variant="destructive">
        <AlertTitle>Error</AlertTitle>
        <AlertDescription>
          Failed to load users. Please try again.
        </AlertDescription>
        <Button onClick={() => window.location.reload()} className="mt-2">
          Retry
        </Button>
      </Alert>
    );
  }

  if (users.length === 0) {
    return (
      <EmptyState 
        icon={<UsersIcon />}
        title="No users yet"
        description="Get started by creating your first user"
        action={<Button>Create User</Button>}
      />
    );
  }

  return (
    <div className="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      {users.map((user) => (
        <UserCard key={user.id} user={user} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Step 2.3: Style and Refine

- Focus on visual design and UX
- Test responsiveness at different screen sizes
- Verify dark mode appearance
- Ensure accessibility (keyboard navigation, ARIA labels)
- Extract reusable sub-components
- Test with different mock scenarios (use `?id=long`, `?id=error`, etc.)

```typescript
// Good: Extracted sub-components
function UserCard({ user }: { user: User }) {
  return (
    <Card>
      <CardHeader>
        <CardTitle>{user.name}</CardTitle>
      </CardHeader>
    </Card>
  );
}

function UserList({ users }: { users: User[] }) {
  return (
    <div className="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      {users.map((user) => (
        <UserCard key={user.id} user={user} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Phase 3: Implement Real Data

Simply replace the mock data in your API route with real database queries. **The component code stays exactly the same.**

### Step 3.1: Update API Route with Database

```typescript
// Before: Mock data
export async function GET(request: NextRequest) {
  const mockUsers = [
    { id: "1", name: "John Doe", email: "john@example.com" },
    { id: "2", name: "Jane Smith", email: "jane@example.com" },
  ];
  
  return NextResponse.json(mockUsers);
}

// After: Real database query - Component unchanged!
import { database } from "@repo/database";

export async function GET(request: NextRequest) {
  try {
    const users = await database
      .selectFrom("user")
      .select(["id", "name", "email", "role", "created_at"])
      .where("deleted_at", "is", null)
      .orderBy("created_at", "desc")
      .execute();

    return NextResponse.json(users);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed to fetch users:", error);
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: "Failed to fetch users" },
      { status: 500 }
    );
  }
}
```

That's it! No component changes, no environment variables, no configuration. Just update the API route.

### Step 3.2: Add Mutations

```typescript
// POST endpoint with real database
export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  try {
    const body = await request.json();
    
    const newUser = await database
      .insertInto("user")
      .values({
        name: body.name,
        email: body.email,
        role: body.role || "user",
      })
      .returningAll()
      .executeTakeFirstOrThrow();

    return NextResponse.json(newUser, { status: 201 });
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed to create user:", error);
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: "Failed to create user" },
      { status: 500 }
    );
  }
}
```

### Step 3.3: Use Server Components When Possible

For Next.js apps, prefer Server Components for data fetching:

```typescript
// Good: Server Component with direct data fetching
export async function UserProfile({ userId }: UserProfileProps) {
  const user = await database
    .selectFrom("user")
    .selectAll()
    .where("id", "=", userId)
    .executeTakeFirst();

  if (!user) {
    return <Alert>User not found</Alert>;
  }

  return <Card>{user.name}</Card>;
}
```

### External APIs Only

If you're consuming an external API you don't control (like Stripe, GitHub, etc.):

```typescript
// Your component still uses your API route
export function StripeCustomer({ customerId }: Props) {
  const { data } = useSWR(`/api/stripe/customers/${customerId}`);
  return <Card>{data.name}</Card>;
}

// Your API route proxies to external API
export async function GET(
  request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: { id: string } }
) {
  // Call external API
  const response = await fetch(
    `https://api.stripe.com/v1/customers/${params.id}`,
    {
      headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY}` },
    }
  );
  
  const customer = await response.json();
  return NextResponse.json(customer);
}
```

MSW only needed for testing external APIs (already configured in `@repo/vitest`).

## Phase 4: Testing

Write tests to verify your components work correctly. Use MSW to mock API route responses in tests.

### Step 4.1: Test UI States with MSW

MSW intercepts your API routes in tests, so you can control responses without changing the component:

```typescript
// Good: Test all UI states using MSW
import { describe, it, expect } from "vitest";
import { render, screen } from "@testing-library/react";
import { server, http, HttpResponse } from "@repo/vitest";
import { UserProfile } from "./UserProfile";

describe("UserProfile", () => {
  it("shows loading state initially", () => {
    render(<UserProfile userId="1" />);
    expect(screen.getByTestId("skeleton")).toBeInTheDocument();
  });

  it("shows user data when loaded", async () => {
    // MSW intercepts /api/users/1 call
    server.use(
      http.get("/api/users/1", () => {
        return HttpResponse.json({
          id: "1",
          name: "John Doe",
          email: "john@example.com",
        });
      })
    );

    render(<UserProfile userId="1" />);
    
    expect(await screen.findByText("John Doe")).toBeInTheDocument();
    expect(screen.getByText("john@example.com")).toBeInTheDocument();
  });

  it("shows error state on failure", async () => {
    // MSW returns error response
    server.use(
      http.get("/api/users/1", () => {
        return new HttpResponse(null, { status: 500 });
      })
    );

    render(<UserProfile userId="1" />);
    
    expect(await screen.findByText(/error/i)).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

**Note:** MSW is configured in `@repo/vitest` and automatically intercepts requests in tests. You don't need any setup - just use `server.use()` to override responses.

### Step 4.2: Test Interactions

```typescript
// Good: Test user interactions
import { userEvent } from "@testing-library/user-event";

it("creates new user on form submit", async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup();
  
  server.use(
    http.post("/api/users", async ({ request }) => {
      const body = await request.json();
      return HttpResponse.json({ id: "new-id", ...body }, { status: 201 });
    })
  );

  render(<UserForm />);
  
  await user.type(screen.getByLabelText("Name"), "John Doe");
  await user.type(screen.getByLabelText("Email"), "john@example.com");
  await user.click(screen.getByRole("button", { name: /submit/i }));

  expect(await screen.findByText("User created successfully")).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

## Best Practices

### UI Development

- **Do:**
  - Create Next.js API route with mock data first
  - Build components that fetch from real endpoints
  - Design all states (loading, error, empty, success) upfront
  - Use shadcn/ui components from `@repo/design`
  - Test responsiveness and dark mode early
  - Extract reusable sub-components

- **Don't:**
  - Hardcode mock data directly in components
  - Use MSW for your own APIs (use Next.js API routes)
  - Forget to handle loading and error states
  - Skip empty state design

### API Development

- **Do:**
  - Always use Next.js API routes for your own APIs
  - Start with mock data, switch to database when ready
  - Add proper error handling and validation
  - Return appropriate HTTP status codes
  - Use TypeScript for request/response types

- **Don't:**
  - Use MSW for internal APIs (only for external APIs)
  - Use environment variables to switch between mock/real data
  - Skip input validation
  - Return sensitive data in API responses
  - Use GET requests for mutations

### Integration

- **Do:**
  - Handle all possible states in the UI
  - Show loading indicators during fetches
  - Provide retry functionality for errors
  - Use Server Components when possible
  - Implement optimistic updates for better UX

- **Don't:**
  - Ignore loading states
  - Show technical error messages to users
  - Make multiple redundant API calls
  - Forget to clean up side effects

## Common Patterns

### Pattern: List with Create

```typescript
// 1. Create API route with mock data - app/api/users/route.ts
export async function GET() {
  // Start with mock data
  return NextResponse.json([
    { id: "1", name: "John Doe", email: "john@example.com" },
    { id: "2", name: "Jane Smith", email: "jane@example.com" },
  ]);
}

// 2. Build component that fetches from API
export function UserList() {
  const { data: users, loading, error } = useSWR("/api/users");
  
  if (loading) return <Skeleton />;
  if (error) return <ErrorMessage />;
  
  return (
    <div className="grid gap-4">
      {users.map(u => <UserCard key={u.id} user={u} />)}
    </div>
  );
}

// 3. Replace with real data - Component unchanged!
export async function GET() {
  const users = await database.selectFrom("user").selectAll().execute();
  return NextResponse.json(users);
}
```

### Pattern: Form with Submission

```typescript
// 1. Create API route with mock - app/api/users/route.ts
export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const body = await request.json();
  
  // Return mock success response
  return NextResponse.json(
    { id: crypto.randomUUID(), ...body },
    { status: 201 }
  );
}

// 2. Build form component that posts to API
export function CreateUserForm() {
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  
  const handleSubmit = async (data: FormData) => {
    setLoading(true);
    try {
      await fetch("/api/users", {
        method: "POST",
        headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
        body: JSON.stringify(data),
      });
      toast.success("User created!");
    } catch (error) {
      toast.error("Failed to create user");
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };
  
  return <Form onSubmit={handleSubmit} loading={loading}>{/* fields */}</Form>;
}

// 3. Add real database - Component unchanged!
export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const body = await request.json();
  const user = await database
    .insertInto("user")
    .values(body)
    .returningAll()
    .executeTakeFirstOrThrow();
    
  return NextResponse.json(user, { status: 201 });
}
```

## Troubleshooting

### Issue: Component doesn't update after API call

**Solution:** Ensure you're updating state or revalidating data after mutations

```typescript
// Good: Revalidate after mutation
const { mutate } = useSWR("/api/users");

async function createUser(data: FormData) {
  await fetch("/api/users", { method: "POST", body: JSON.stringify(data) });
  mutate(); // Revalidate the data
}
```

### Issue: MSW handlers not working

**Solution:** Ensure handlers are defined and server is started

```typescript
// Check: handlers are exported
export const handlers = [/* ... */];

// Check: setup.ts starts the server
beforeAll(() => server.listen());
```

### Issue: Loading state flickers

**Solution:** Add minimum display time for loading states

```typescript
// Good: Prevent flash of loading state
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

useEffect(() => {
  const fetchData = async () => {
    const [data] = await Promise.all([
      fetch("/api/data"),
      new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 300)), // Min 300ms
    ]);
    setData(data);
    setLoading(false);
  };
  
  fetchData();
}, []);
```
